r:roles></gtr:personRole><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/1B7D7562-C863-4F7E-BB20-5CDA4F5C4FDC"><gtr:id>1B7D7562-C863-4F7E-BB20-5CDA4F5C4FDC</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Susan Fairley</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Murray</gtr:surname><gtr:orcidId>0000-0003-0093-3815</gtr:orcidId><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/projects?ref=ES%2FH032657%2F1"><gtr:id>8F32B1CA-9138-4C7A-A050-9C200A1C5B4D</gtr:id><gtr:title>India's challenge in a globalizing healthcare economy: social science directions</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/H032657/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>India will be the third largest economy in the world by 2020. Healthcare is one of the largest sectors in terms of revenue and employment, and is expanding rapidly. But despite rapid economic growth there are great social and economic inequalities. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The complex relationship between India's adaptation to the new global environment and Indian population heath needs and aspirations, local and international health systems, and healthcare related industries, is one that social scientists are beginning to study. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The network proposes to strengthen and extend this activity by:&lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>Bringing together and examining the diverse literatures.&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>Hosting workshops in London and New Delhi to enable key researchers from across the social sciences in India and the UK, and potential users of their work,&amp;nbsp; to come together to discuss existing findings, emerging topic areas, and the new methods that may be required for investigating these.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>Publishing findings as Open Access papers in a journal special issue.&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>Developing future research priorities.&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>

&lt;p>The network is coordinated by researchers from three key universities which bring together interests in social science, healthcare and health policy, globalization, and India&amp;nbsp; -&amp;nbsp; King's College London, Jawaharlal Nehru University, New Delhi, and London School of Economics&amp;nbsp;and Political Science. &lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2011-01-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2010-02-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>60639</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Symposium on health systems, health economies and globalisation : social science perspectives : symposium 1 London</gtr:description><gtr:form>Scientific meeting (conference/symposium etc.)</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>International</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>E70B655E-6ADF-4E1B-8856-DACF478D01A9</gtr:id><gtr:impact>This, the first of two symposiums, brings together a mix of UK, Indian and other social scientists, and users of social science. Provisional themes: Globalisation and India's changing healthcare landscapes; Globalisation and the governance of new technologies; Understanding influences on access to medicines in a globalised market; Problematising global health policy; Transnational healthcare markets &amp;amp; providers; Transnational healthcare markets &amp;amp; users.

The best papers were developed into a peer reviewed journal special issue.
